0–1140","1015–1070":"1015–1070","1080":"1080","from about 1069 to 1080":"from about 1069 to 1080","about 1070":"about 1070","about 1080":"about 1080","1066":"1066","1086":"1086","1140":"1140","1050":"1050","1070":"1070","1015":"1015","1112":"1112","1045":"1045","about 1045":"about 1045","Cottingham, East Riding, Yorkshire, England":"Cottingham, Yorkshire, England","Skipwith, Yorkshire, England":"Skipwith, Yorkshire, England","Cottingham, Yorkshire, England":"Cottingham, Yorkshire, England","Cottingham, Yorkshire, , England":"Cottingham, Yorkshire East Riding, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hugh","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Hugues</i>, <i>Hugo</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’. It was originally a short form of various compound names containing this element. This was borne by the aristocracy of medieval France, adopted by the Normans, and introduced by them to Britain. It was consistently one of the most popular boys' names in the Middle Ages in England, but fell out of favour in the 16th century until it was revived in the 20th century. Little Hugh of Lincoln was a child supposed in the Middle Ages to have been murdered by Jews in about  1255 , a legend responsible for several outbursts of anti-Semitism at various times. The story is referred to by  Chaucer  in The Prioress's Tale. He is not to be confused with  St Hugh of Lincoln  (  1140–1200 ), bishop of Lincoln (  1186–1200 ), who was noted for his charity and good works, his piety, and his defence of the Church against the State. Since the later Middle Ages <i>Hugh</i> has also been used as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Aodh ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":21,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705183,"age":41,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Hugh FitzBaldric was born about 1045, in Cottingham, Yorkshire, England as the son of Baldric de Lascelles. He married Emma Lascelles. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. In 1069, his occupation is listed as sheriff of yorkshire . He died in 1086, in Cottingham, Yorkshire East Riding, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 42."},"et":{"about 1045–1086":"umbes 1045–1086","1045–1086":"1045–1086","1050–Female":"1050–Surnud","1080–1112":"1080–1112","1080–1140":"1080–1140","1015–1070":"1015–1070","1080":"1080","from about 1069 to 1080":"umbes 1069 kuni 1080","about 1070":"umbes 1070","about 1080":"umbes 1080","1066":"1066","1086":"1086","1140":"1140","1050":"1050","1070":"1070","1015":"1015","1112":"1112","1045":"1045","about 1045":"umbes 1045","Cottingham, East Riding, Yorkshire, England":"Cottingham, Yorkshire, England","Skipwith, Yorkshire, England":"Skipwith, Yorkshire, England","Cottingham, Yorkshire, England":"Cottingham, Yorkshire, England","Cottingham, Yorkshire, , England":"Cottingham, Yorkshire East Riding, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1045–1086":"noin 1045–1086","1045–1086":"1045–1086","1050–Fema